Doc,<br><br>
The only thing that has changed is  my newfound feeling of acceptance by other vets who don't necessarily agree with my rejection of the Vietnam War, yet who understand where I am coming from. To be *understood* is important to me.<br><br>
There have been several times where I have been engaged in disagreements with others on this site - simply because I disagreed. I am not here to change anyone's mind - rather my purpose is to promote understanding in others - preferably in an atmosphere of fairness and civility. <br><br>
I am well satisfied that my opinions are known! I am not interested in maintaining an adversarial type of dialogue, which tends to promote antagonism more reminiscent of broken records than understanding. Above all else, my mission IS NOT to run anyone from this site. That is why I don't engage in insults and intimidation by namecalling.<br><br>
I am also well aware that my opinions are better received because I did serve in Vietnam and have a truer perspective.<br>
Class Lass should consider the same.<br><br>
I feel that there is plenty of room for different opinions on this site - yours included. If it is, as you say, that some vets feel anger at what is transpiring here, then where are their voices? Why don't they step forward and object to whatever they find objectionable? Why is it that *you* have to make mention of this?<br><br>
I have no problem with the opinions of Class Lass. However, I feel that the first step in acquiring credibility and respect is for someone to attach their name and email address to their opinions - especially those which include controversial topics and criticism. Why is this hard for you to understand? About a week ago, you said as much in your harsh message to the vets on this site - more specifically to SW.<br><br>
In conclusion, as I have said numerous times on this site, if someone expects to exchange ideas with me in this forum, they need to post their name and email address. It's that simple.<br><br>

<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


